      <h3>The potential of postal workers as part of senior care</h3>

      
      <p>
        Across the globe, postal companies have successfully demonstrated success 
        in expanding their businesses, notably through senior check-in services
        delivered by letter carriers. Examples include the ‚ÄúMimamori‚Äù program from Japan
        Post, and ‚ÄúVeiller sur mes parents‚Äù program from the French La Poste. 
        <br /><br />
        But how does this evidence that such a service would benefit Canada Post? Through investigating
        potential stakeholders - postal workers, and those in senior care - we discovered the following insights:
      </p>

      <h3><i>87% of Canadians trust their mail carriers.</i></h3>
      <p>
        Through a special report released in 2023, our team discovered that the
         National Institute on Ageing (NIA), a research centre based
        at Toronto Metropolitan University, advocates that Canada Post is in
        a unique position to deliver such a service. Citing a poll conducted by Leger
        conducted in 2015, they state that letter carriers are amongst the most trusted
        professions in Canada, with 87% of Canadians saying they trusted their mail
        carriers.
      </p>

      <h3><i>Canadians are getting older.</i></h3>
        <p>Furthermore, within the Canadian context, Statistics Canada has
        reported that 1 in 4 Canadians will be over the age
        of 65 by 2030 (in comparison to 15.3% in 2013), and the NIA and Canadian
        Medical Association reporting that 96% of Canadians want to age at home
        for as long as possible.</p>

      <h3><i>Postal worker unions have been advocating for such a service.</i></h3>
        <p>
        It was also promising that we were able to discover interest for this service amongst employees of Canada Post as well - 
         a report written in 2016, with several follow-ups since (the latest one written in 2023), evidenced to us 
         that the Canadian Union of Postal Workers has been continuously advocating
          for Canada Post to leverage its unique positioning and network of over (12540
          + 28,400) letter carriers to establish a check-in service for seniors for several years now.
        </p>
        <p></p>        However, in order for Canada Post to properly adopt a senior-oriented check-in service, 
        there were areas of consideration that would have to be designed to. Upon presenting our idea in-class, 
        we were met with a few concerns from peers that helped narrowed down these concerns: 
        How would they prevent this service from interfering with what's currently available to Canadians?
        How would the service be modelled so that it would avoid invasiveness? 
        What sort of unique needs and wants would we need to address in re-creating a foreign service for a Canadian demographic?
        <br/><br/>
      </p>
